```protobuf
message User {
  string name = 1;
  int32 age = 2;
  repeated string tags = 3;
  map<string, string> metadata = 4;
  optional string bio = 5;
}
```
**message** defines structured data. Field numbers identify fields in binary encoding — never reuse deleted numbers.

```protobuf
service UserService {
  rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (User);
  rpc ListUsers(ListUsersRequest) returns (stream User);
  rpc Upload(stream Chunk) returns (UploadResponse);
  rpc Chat(stream Msg) returns (stream Msg);
}
```
**service** defines gRPC endpoints. Four patterns: unary, server streaming, client streaming, bidirectional.

```protobuf
rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (User);
rpc ListUsers(Empty) returns (stream User);
```
**rpc** defines a remote procedure call within a service. Input and output are message types. `stream` enables streaming.

```protobuf
enum Status {
  STATUS_UNSPECIFIED = 0;
  STATUS_ACTIVE = 1;
  STATUS_INACTIVE = 2;
}
```
**enum** defines named constants. Zero value is required and should be UNSPECIFIED. Use type name as prefix.

```protobuf
message SearchResult {
  oneof result {
    User user = 1;
    Group group = 2;
    string error = 3;
  }
}
```
**oneof** enforces that at most one field in the group is set. Setting one clears the others. Saves memory.

```protobuf
message User {
  repeated string tags = 1;
  repeated Address addresses = 2;
}
```
**repeated** marks a field as a list (zero or more elements). Order is preserved. Can contain scalars or messages.

```protobuf
message Config {
  map<string, string> properties = 1;
  map<int32, Feature> features = 2;
}
```
**map** defines key-value pairs. Keys must be integral or string types. Values can be any type except another map.

```protobuf
message User {
  optional string nickname = 1;
  optional int32 age = 2;
}
```
**optional** (proto3) enables presence tracking. Without it, default values are indistinguishable from unset fields.

```protobuf
message Example {
  reserved 5, 10 to 12;
  reserved "old_field", "legacy";
}
```
**reserved** prevents reuse of deleted field numbers or names. Protects against data corruption from old messages.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";
import "other/messages.proto";
import public "shared/types.proto";
```
**import** includes definitions from other .proto files. `import public` re-exports the imported definitions.

```protobuf
option java_package = "com.example.proto";
option go_package = "github.com/user/repo/pb";
option java_multiple_files = true;
```
**option** configures code generation. Language-specific options control package names, output structure, etc.

```protobuf
message Example {
  string name = 1;   // 1-15: one byte (frequent fields)
  int32 count = 16;  // 16-2047: two bytes
  // 19000-19999: reserved by protobuf
}
```
**Field numbers** identify fields in binary format. Use 1-15 for frequent fields (more efficient). Never reuse numbers.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";
import "google/protobuf/duration.proto";
import "google/protobuf/empty.proto";
import "google/protobuf/wrappers.proto";
import "google/protobuf/any.proto";
import "google/protobuf/struct.proto";
```
**Well-known types** are standard utility messages. Timestamp for dates, Empty for void, wrappers for nullable scalars.

```protobuf
// Numeric: double, float, int32, int64, uint32, uint64
//          sint32, sint64 (efficient for negatives)
//          fixed32, fixed64, sfixed32, sfixed64
// Other: bool, string, bytes
```
**Scalar types** — choose based on value range and encoding efficiency.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";

message Event {
  string name = 1;
  google.protobuf.Timestamp created_at = 2;
}
```
**Timestamp** represents a point in time with seconds and nanoseconds since Unix epoch.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/duration.proto";

message Config {
  google.protobuf.Duration timeout = 1;
}
```
**Duration** represents a signed length of time with seconds and nanoseconds.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/any.proto";

message Response {
  google.protobuf.Any data = 1;
}
```
**Any** wraps an arbitrary message with a type URL. Use for polymorphic fields when the type isn't known at compile time.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/empty.proto";

service MyService {
  rpc Ping(google.protobuf.Empty) returns (google.protobuf.Empty);
}
```
**Empty** represents a message with no fields. Use for RPCs with no meaningful request/response.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/struct.proto";

message Config {
  google.protobuf.Struct metadata = 1;  // arbitrary JSON-like data
}
```
**Struct** represents untyped JSON-like data. Use when the schema is dynamic or unknown at compile time.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/field_mask.proto";

message UpdateUserRequest {
  User user = 1;
  google.protobuf.FieldMask update_mask = 2;
}
```
**FieldMask** specifies which fields to update in a partial update request. Standard pattern for PATCH operations.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/wrappers.proto";

message Config {
  google.protobuf.Int32Value max_retries = 1;
  google.protobuf.StringValue label = 2;
}
```
**Wrapper types** (Int32Value, StringValue, etc.) provide nullable scalars. Absent wrapper = null, present = has value.

```protobuf
message Point {
  double latitude = 1;
  double longitude = 2;
}
```
**double** is a 64-bit IEEE 754 floating point number. Use for precise decimal values.

```protobuf
message Sensor {
  float temperature = 1;
}
```
**float** is a 32-bit IEEE 754 floating point. Less precise than double but uses less space.

```protobuf
message Item {
  int32 quantity = 1;
}
```
**int32** is a variable-length signed 32-bit integer. Inefficient for negative numbers — use `sint32` for those.

```protobuf
message File {
  int64 size_bytes = 1;
}
```
**int64** is a variable-length signed 64-bit integer. Use for large values like file sizes or timestamps.

```protobuf
message Config {
  uint32 port = 1;
}
```
**uint32** is a variable-length unsigned 32-bit integer. Use for values that are always non-negative.

```protobuf
message Feature {
  bool enabled = 1;
}
```
**bool** represents true/false. Default value is false in proto3.

```protobuf
message User {
  string name = 1;
  string email = 2;
}
```
**string** must be valid UTF-8 encoded text. Use `bytes` for arbitrary binary data.

```protobuf
message File {
  bytes content = 1;
}
```
**bytes** holds arbitrary binary data. No UTF-8 requirement. Use for file contents, hashes, etc.

```protobuf
service Chat {
  rpc Send(stream Message) returns (stream Message);
}
```
**stream** enables streaming in RPCs. Can be on request (client streaming), response (server streaming), or both (bidirectional).

```protobuf
// Proto2 only:
extend google.protobuf.MethodOptions {
  optional string auth_level = 50000;
}
```
**extend** adds custom fields to existing messages (proto2). In proto3, use custom options with extensions.

```protobuf
message User {
  string name = 1;
  string old_email = 2 [deprecated = true];
  string email = 3;
}
```
**[deprecated = true]** marks a field as deprecated. Generates deprecation warnings in client code.

```protobuf
message User {
  string user_name = 1 [json_name = "userName"];
}
```
**[json_name]** overrides the JSON field name. By default, proto field names use camelCase in JSON.

```protobuf
// Proto3 default values:
// string: ""    int32: 0    bool: false
// enum: first value (0)
// message: null  repeated: empty list
// bytes: empty bytes
```
**Default values** in proto3 are always zero/empty. There's no way to distinguish "not set" from default without `optional`.

```protobuf
message Order {
  message LineItem {
    string product = 1;
    int32 quantity = 2;
  }
  repeated LineItem items = 1;
}
```
**Nested messages** are defined inside another message. Referenced as `Order.LineItem` from outside.

```protobuf
// Wire types:
// 0: Varint (int32, int64, uint32, uint64, sint32, sint64, bool, enum)
// 1: 64-bit (fixed64, sfixed64, double)
// 2: Length-delimited (string, bytes, messages, repeated)
// 5: 32-bit (fixed32, sfixed32, float)
```
**Wire format** uses 5 wire types for binary encoding. Varint encoding makes small numbers compact.

```protobuf
message Delta {
  sint32 offset = 1;
}
```
**sint32** uses ZigZag encoding, making negative values much more compact than `int32`. Use when values are frequently negative.

```protobuf
message Hash {
  fixed64 value = 1;
}
```
**fixed64** is always 8 bytes. More efficient than `int64` when values are frequently > 2^56.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/descriptor.proto";

extend google.protobuf.FieldOptions {
  optional bool sensitive = 50000;
}

message User {
  string password = 1 [(sensitive) = true];
}
```
**Custom options** extend built-in options for fields, messages, services, etc. Use high field numbers (50000+).
